===========================================================
                     EXPLANATION
===========================================================

1. PRODUCER
-----------
- Producer sends messages to Kafka topics
- Example:
  producer.send(new ProducerRecord<>("orders", key, value));

- If key is present → same key goes to same partition (ordering maintained)
- If no key → round-robin distribution

-----------------------------------------------------------

2. KAFKA BROKER
---------------
- Kafka broker stores messages
- Messages are organized into topics
- Each topic is divided into partitions

WHY PARTITIONS?
- Enables parallel processing
- Improves scalability
- Maintains ordering within a partition

-----------------------------------------------------------

3. TOPICS & PARTITIONS
----------------------
Example:
  Topic: orders
  Partitions: P0, P1, P2

- Messages are distributed across partitions
- Each partition is an ordered log (0,1,2,3...)

-----------------------------------------------------------

4. CONSUMER GROUP
-----------------
- A consumer group = multiple consumers working together
- They share the load of reading partitions

IMPORTANT RULE:
  1 Partition = Only 1 Consumer (within a group)

-----------------------------------------------------------

5. CONSUMER SCENARIOS
---------------------

Case 1:
  3 partitions, 3 consumers
  → Each consumer gets 1 partition ✅

Case 2:
  3 partitions, 4 consumers
  → 1 consumer remains idle ❌

Case 3:
  3 partitions, 2 consumers
  → Consumers handle multiple partitions

-----------------------------------------------------------

6. MULTIPLE CONSUMER GROUPS (PUB-SUB)
-------------------------------------
- Same topic can be consumed by multiple groups

Example:
  orders topic:
    Group A → Payment Service
    Group B → Analytics Service
    Group C → Notification Service

- Each group gets ALL messages
- Each group maintains its own offset

-----------------------------------------------------------

7. OFFSET
---------
- Offset = position of message in partition

Example:
  Partition 0:
    [0] msg1
    [1] msg2
    [2] msg3

- Consumer tracks last read offset
- Stored in Kafka internally

-----------------------------------------------------------

8. DATA FLOW SUMMARY
--------------------
  Producer
     ↓
  Topic
     ↓
  Partitions
     ↓
  Consumer Group
     ↓
  Consumers (parallel processing)

-----------------------------------------------------------

9. IMPORTANT INTERVIEW POINTS
-----------------------------
✔ Ordering → Only within partition
✔ Parallelism → Through partitions
✔ Scaling → Increase partitions
✔ Consumer groups → Load balancing
✔ Multiple groups → Pub-Sub model
✔ Rebalancing → Happens when consumers join/leave

-----------------------------------------------------------

10. INTERVIEW ANSWER (SHORT)
----------------------------
Kafka producer sends messages to a topic.
Topics are divided into partitions.
Consumers are grouped into consumer groups.
Each partition is consumed by only one consumer within a group.
Multiple consumer groups can independently consume the same topic.

